## AI AGENT BEHAVIOR RULES

1. **Read before write** — Always read the relevant existing file completely before modifying it
2. **Migrations are permanent** — Never edit an existing migration file. Always create a new one
3. **Test your routes** — After adding routes, verify with `rails routes | grep your_route`
4. **Check if it exists** — Before building a feature, search the codebase. Chatwoot may already have it
5. **Namespace HOF code** — All HOF-specific code should be in `HOF::` module namespace or prefixed with `hof_`
6. **No monkey patching** — Do not reopen core Rails or Chatwoot classes. Use concerns/modules
7. **Ask before DB changes** — Any new migration that modifies existing tables → ask user first
8. **Keep upstream clean** — Commit HOF changes on a separate branch `hof-main`, never on `develop`
9. **One thing at a time** — Do not make multiple unrelated changes in one go
10. **If unsure → ask** — Better to ask than to break something in production

---

## BRANCH STRATEGY
```
develop          → Upstream Chatwoot (pull updates here)
hof-main         → HOF production branch (our customizations)
hof-feature/xxx  → Individual feature branches
```

When Chatwoot releases an update:
1. Pull into `develop`
2. Merge `develop` into `hof-main`
3. Resolve conflicts (should be minimal if rules followed)

---

## DEPLOYMENT (Railway)
- Production URL: https://inbox.hofmigration.com
- Platform: Railway.app
- Services: Chatwoot web + Sidekiq + PostgreSQL + Valkey (Redis)
- Deploy: Push to `hof-main` → Railway auto-deploys
- Env vars: Managed in Railway dashboard (never commit .env to git)

